# Backend layering

1. Preserve explicit bounded contexts: `wb-sync`, `wb-clusters`, `catalog`, `pricing`, `stocks`, `orders`, `analytics`, `audit`.
2. Controllers handle transport only: route, DTO, auth/guard boundary, and response code.
3. Services own business rules, orchestration, retries, and cross-step coordination.
4. Repositories own direct SQL/ORM queries and read/write persistence access.
5. Builders and mappers shape DTOs or read-model responses; they should not own side effects.
6. Jobs, queues, backfills, and materializers belong to explicit write/background services, not to user-facing read endpoints.
7. Direct SQL, external API branching, or heavy business decisions must not live in controllers.
8. Use dependency injection instead of manual object construction inside feature flows.
9. User-facing `GET` read paths must resolve stored snapshots or explicit missing states only; diagnostic live read-model access stays on separate routes/services.
10. Security belongs to the server boundary: validate input DTOs, keep secrets in env/config, and keep access checks explicit at controller/guard/service boundaries.
11. When backend contracts change, update DTOs, builders, tests/checks, and all readers together.
